  m_Script: {fileID: 11500000, guid: cd20df6c9479f3d449851f4ca53de79e, type: 3}
  m_Name: PlantsBook
  m_EditorClassIdentifier: 
  bookTitle: Plants
  spreads:
  - layout: {fileID: 6211519498159910813, guid: cc6383de98fd6294388821de6cde789f, type: 3}
    textA: 'Some of the local plants have changed recently. I have tried to record
      their changes in this journal. These are not plants. They imitate structure,
      but not purpose.


      Roots without soil.

      Growth without light....'
    textB: They react....not to water, not to time. To us....
    textC: 
    textD: 
    imageA: {fileID: -8782625415207700165, guid: a6bf0ec97b5fbac49aa2cb19938f0341, type: 3}
    imageB: {fileID: 5196001237837151643, guid: 8f14be6d6ec0ca44198dbd2a3f825295, type: 3}
    imageC: {fileID: 0}
    imageD: {fileID: 0}
  - layout: {fileID: 4370654923283873279, guid: 23277499e8242d7408e073be2ad16ba4, type: 3}
    textA: Flower Plant
    textB: 'Some specimens recoil from sudden illumination. Not sustained light,
      but interuption.


      This explains why they are able to survive in the
      daylight.'
    textC: 'A steady beam did nothing. But brief flashes....force it to contract?

      Like
      blinking at something that shouldn''t be there. It seemed to shrink when I
      my light shined over it, after three times it died.'
    textD: It didn't work on all the new plants though...only the large flower looking
      one.
    imageA: {fileID: 6941706853065814016, guid: cac120f03edfaff46aba647ba6c2fb65, type: 3}
    imageB: {fileID: 0}
    imageC: {fileID: 0}
    imageD: {fileID: 0}
  - layout: {fileID: 4469434606004700145, guid: e5c24f74ef90d13428ffc21800898f8c, type: 3}
    textA: Flytrap
    textB: Do not get close!
    textC: 'There seems to be pale variants that do not photosynthesize. The look
      like venus flytraps but larger, they avoid natural light entirely!

      They
      seem to prefer something else...perhaps their large mouth will explain?'
    textD: 'Under the inspection light, they collapse rapidly. Not a burn, but erased..

      As
      if it exposed it for what they really are. Perhaps the UV is responsible for
      why they avoid the daylight?'
    imageA: {fileID: 8390678095838365347, guid: cde67fe0ce6d2214284b546b67507507, type: 3}
    imageB: {fileID: 0}
    imageC: {fileID: 0}
    imageD: {fileID: 0}
  - layout: {fileID: 6211519498159910813, guid: cc6383de98fd6294388821de6cde789f, type: 3}
    textA: 'Do not assume they behave like plants! Watering them made them worse.


      Fire
      was....inconclusive.

      Sometimes effective.

      Sometimes it spread.'
    textB: Havn't tried overwatering. Must try as soon as I can!
    textC: 
    textD: 
    imageA: {fileID: -7845495922271660370, guid: e6ebebfbd034ea848b7eecb414a2f126, type: 3}
    imageB: {fileID: 0}
    imageC: {fileID: 0}
    imageD: {fileID: 0}
  - layout: {fileID: 3671605574920047432, guid: b191c64eb2c198f428530da38559661f, type: 3}
    textA: Pitcher
    textB: 'Cutting the surface does nothing. It grows back faster than it is removed.
      But the structure is not uniform. There are points where everything connects.
      If I break those, the whole thing falls. It seems to only work on the large
      pitcher type variant....

      I have crossed out its weak points in the image
      to the left.'
    textC: 
    textD: 
    imageA: {fileID: -7201280966428126598, guid: 065aad82e2f7c794b8ca08b457467e37, type: 3}
    imageB: {fileID: -131896887491537849, guid: 9ed1b74ed00a32e41906a8cbbdd50064, type: 3}
    imageC: {fileID: 0}
    imageD: {fileID: 0}
